{"warnings":{"query":{"*":"Formatting of continuation data will be changing soon. To continue using the current formatting, use the 'rawcontinue' parameter. To begin using the new format, pass an empty string for 'continue' in the initial query."}},"query":{"pages":{"8816289":{"pageid":8816289,"ns":0,"title":"Hulkbusters","revisions":[{"contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{About|the Marvel Comics organizations|information on Iron Man's Hulkbuster armor|Iron Man's armor}}\n{{Refimprove|date=November 2009}}\n\n'''Hulkbusters''' is the name of three [[fiction]]al organizations that have appeared in various [[comic book]] series published by [[Marvel Comics]]. All three groups exist within Marvel's [[shared universe]] known as the [[Marvel Universe]] and are so-named for their attempts to battle [[Hulk (comics)|Hulk]].\n\n==Fictional history==\n===The U.S. military's Hulkbusters===\nThe original Hulkbusters were a large joint [[task force]] consisting of both U.S. Army and Air Force personnel, whose primary purpose was to capture or if necessary, destroy the Hulk. Their headquarters was the Hulkbuster Base in New Mexico, resembling a [[peace symbols#The peace sign|peace sign]] (also known as [[Gamma Base]]), after it was damaged by the Hulk,{{Issue|date=November 2009}} and they were commanded by General [[Thunderbolt Ross|\"Thunderbolt\" Ross]], General [[John Ryker|Ryker]] and Major [[Glenn Talbot]]. Hulkbuster Base was later demolished by the [[U-Foes]].<ref>''[[Hulk (comics)|Incredible Hulk]]'' #277 (Nov 1982)</ref> After Bruce Banner, the Hulk\u2019s alter-ego, achieved a state in which his normal intelligence and personality remained dominant while in Hulk form, he received a presidential pardon and the Hulkbusters were disbanded.<ref>''[[Hulk (comics)|Incredible Hulk]]'' #279 (Jan 1983)</ref>\n\nWhile this operation was active, [[Clay Quartermain]] was the [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]] liaison to the Hulkbusters operation.\n\nGamma Base, located in Death Valley, Nevada, is dedicated to the capturing and curing the Incredible Hulk.\n\nOriginally, Gamma Base was Project Greenskin: Hulkbuster Base and it was the base for the Hulkbusters. The US Government shut it down and it was opened again for Bruce Banner's Project: Hulkbuster.{{Issue|date=November 2009}} When that group broke up, it was shut down again.{{Issue|date=November 2009}} Once again it was re-opened for the use of Operation: Zero Tolerance.{{Issue|date=November 2009}}\n\n===Banner\u2019s Hulkbusters===\nAfter the Hulk reverted to his bestial personality, he was captured by [[Doc Samson]].<ref>''[[Hulk (comics)|Incredible Hulk]]'' #314 (Dec 1985)</ref> Samson persuaded the government to rebuild and finance Gamma Base. There, Samson managed to separate Banner and the Hulk into two distinct beings, although the Hulk was able to escape.<ref>''[[Hulk (comics)|Incredible Hulk]]'' #315 (Jan 1986)</ref> Banner was named the leader of this iteration of the Hulkbusters,<ref>''Incredible Hulk'' #317</ref> which first appeared in ''[[Hulk (comics)|Incredible Hulk]]'' #317, created by [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]] (Mar 1986).<ref>''[[Hulk (comics)|Incredible Hulk]]'' #317 (Mar 1986)</ref>\n\nMembers of this group of Hulkbusters included:\n\n* Craig Saunders, Jr. \u2013 Demolition expert (later known as [[Redeemer (Marvel Comics)|Redeemer]])\n* [[List of Marvel Comics characters: P#Carolyn Parmenter|Carolyn Parmenter]] \u2013 Marine scientist\n* Samuel J. La Roquette \u2013 Explorer (later known as [[Rock (Marvel Comics)|Rock]])\n* [[List of Marvel Comics characters: M#Armand Martel|Armand Martel]] \u2013 Xenobiologist\n* [[List of Marvel Comics characters: T#Hideko Takata|Hideko Takata]] \u2013 Professor of geophysics\n\nSaunders, Jr. and La Roquette later became '''Rock and Redeemer''', a supervillain team who faced the Hulk on various occasions,<ref>''Incredible Hulk'' #345</ref><ref>''Incredible Hulk'' #366</ref><ref>''Incredible Hulk'' #398</ref> after much of Banner's HB team were slain in Hulk's destruction.<ref>''Incredible Hulk'' #343</ref> Rock had an external hide made of deadly minerals which can be used to impale and grow in size. Redeemer had an exoskeletal suit with weapons like repulsor blasters, and rocket fuel. [[Leader (comics)|The Leader]] later recruited them into \"New Freehold\" along with the [[Riot Squad (comics)|Riot Squad]],{{Issue|date=September 2009}} and they haven't been seen since.\n\n===S.H.I.E.L.D's Hulkbusters===\nHulk's exile from Earth by the [[Illuminati (comics)|Illuminati]] brought forth an unexpected consequence: Hulk's rogues' gallery began running wild. As a result, [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]] formed a team called the Hulkbusters to capture these villains and implant them with nanotechnology to nullify their powers.<ref>''Incredible Hulk'' Vol. 2 #106</ref> The team was led by Agent Clay Quartermain and members included [[List of Marvel Comics characters: A#Agent Cheesecake|Agent Cheesecake]], Agent Crimson, and [[She-Hulk]].\n\n==Other versions==\n===Ultimate Marvel===\nIn the [[Ultimate Marvel]] Universe, Hulkbuster teams exist and primarily serve Nick Fury and S.H.I.E.L.D. Hulkbuster Units have been used to take down major threats such as [[Alternative versions of the Green Goblin#Ultimate Marvel|Norman Osborn]], [[Harry Osborn#Ultimate Harry Osborn|Harry Osborn]], and [[Alternative versions of Venom#Ultimate Spider-Man|Venom]]. <ref>''[[Ultimate Spider-Man]]'' #100</ref>\n\n==In other media==\n===Television===\n* The Hulkbusters were recurring antagonists in the first season of the 1996 animated series ''[[The Incredible Hulk (1996 TV series)|The Incredible Hulk]]''. They were used by Thunderbolt Ross and [[S.H.I.E.L.D.]] agent [[Gabe Jones|Gabriel Jones]] in tracking down Bruce Banner. Dr. Craig Saunders Jr. and Dr. Samuel J. La Roquette (later known as Rock and Redeemer) were mentioned as members.\n\n* The Hulkbusters appear in the ''[[The Avengers: Earth's Mightiest Heroes]]'' episode \"Hulk vs. the World\".\n\n* The Hulkbusters appear in the ''[[Ultimate Spider-Man (TV series)|Ultimate Spider-Man]]'' episode \"The Incredible Spider-Hulk\".\n\n* The Hulkbusters appear in the ''[[Hulk and the Agents of S.M.A.S.H.]]'' episode \"Hulk-Busted\". The featured Hulkbusters are modeled to take on the Agents of S.M.A.S.H. in case they got out of control. Leader hijacks the Hulkbusters to attack the Agents of S.M.A.S.H. Iron Man comes to their aid and helps to fight the Hulkbusters. Iron Man uses his holograms to fool the Hulkbusters into thinking that they destroyed them. Iron Man showed them footage on the Stealth-Bot infecting a virus in the Hulkbusters armor so that they can be controlled from the outside. Using parts from the defeated Hulkbusters, the Agents of S.M.A.S.H. use them to take on the remaining Hulkbusters. The Hulkbusters then activate magnetizing beams to combine all of them into one giant Hulkbuster as it captures Iron Man and flies off. The Agents of S.M.A.S.H. pursue the giant Hulkbuster where Iron Man states that his Arc Reactor is being used to power the giant Hulkbuster and use it as a bomb where Iron Man and the Agents of S.M.A.S.H. will be blamed for the city's destruction. After freeing Iron Man, Hulk redirects the defeated Hulkbuster into the river. Iron Man states that he will dismantle the Hulkbusters, but Hulk insists that he keep one Hulkbuster in case he gets out of control. In the episode \"Homecoming,\" Abomination gains some Hulkbusters that obey his commands after he was pardoned and reinstated into the U.S. Army. Abomination used the Hulkbusters to take over Vista Verde. When the Agents of S.M.A.S.H. return, they end up having to fight Abomination and the Hulkbusters. After the Gamma Hammer that came under Abomination's control is destroyed by Hulk, the rest of the Hulkbusters were destroyed by A-Bomb, She-Hulk, and Skaar.\n\n* The Hulkbusters appear in the ''[[Avengers Assemble (TV series)|Avengers Assemble]]'' episode \"Head to Head.\" When MODOK used the Mind Infinity Gem to take control of S.H.I.E.L.D., he unleashed some S.H.I.E.L.D. Hulkbusters on them.\n\n===Video games===\n* The Hulkbusters appeared in [[Hulk (video game)|the ''Hulk'' 2003 game]]. They are depicted as military units controlled by [[John Ryker#Video games|General Ryker]].\n\n* The Hulkbusters appear in ''[[The Incredible Hulk: Ultimate Destruction]]'' as part of General Ross and [[Abomination (comics)|Director Emil Blonsky]]'s efforts to capture the Hulk. These Hulkbusters are soldiers mentally controlling mechanical armor of varying sizes and capabilities; some missions require the player to recover or destroy prototype technology that will be used on the Hulkbusters to limit the threat that they will pose to the player later in the game.\n\n* Armored Hulkbusters appear in ''[[The Incredible Hulk (2008 video game)|The Incredible Hulk]]'' video game with two of them voiced by [[S. Scott Bullock]] and [[Chris Edgerly]]. These suits are identified as [[Stark Industries|StarkTech]] models. Hulk had to protect the Hulkbuster technology from [[Enclave (comics)|Enclave]] and later helps them fight Enclave's F-POD. A Hulkbuster under Major [[Glenn Talbot]]'s control was a mini-boss for Hulk until Betty Ross reveals herself to the Hulkbuster. Glenn Talbot also powers a nuclear-powered Hulkbuster armor in his fight with the Hulk. A version of [[Iron Man]]'s [[Iron Man's armor|Hulkbuster armor]] appears as a playable [[Player character|secret character]] if there is a [[saved game]] for the 2008 ''[[Iron Man (video game)|Iron Man]]'' video game present on the same [[Memory card#Memory cards in video game consoles|memory card]] used for ''The Incredible Hulk''.\n\n===Novels===\n* In the [[novelization]] of the 2008 film ''[[The Incredible Hulk (film)|The Incredible Hulk]]'' (written by [[Peter David]], a noted contributor to the Hulk's comics history), two members of a military strike team sent to capture the Hulk are named \"Saunders\" and \"Laroquette\" after members of Banner's Hulkbusters (the characters are unnamed in the theatrical release of the film).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://marvel.com/universe/Hulkbusters Hulkbusters] at Marvel.com\n\n{{Hulk}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional organizations in Marvel Comics]]\n[[Category:Fictional soldiers]]\n[[Category:Fictional special forces personnel]]\n[[Category:Marvel Comics supervillains]]"}]}}}}